title: My Lab Journal
text: This is a template example for lab journaling. Students in the data science courses at the Institute of Entrepreneurship will use this template to learn R for business analytics. Students can replace this text as they wish.

title: My Lab Journal
text:
How to use

Accept the assignment and get your own github repo.
Blog/journal what you are doing in R, by editing the .qmd files.
See the links page for lots of helpful links on learning R.
Change everything to make it your own.
Make sure to render you website every time before you want to upload changes.

library("dagitty")
library("ggdag")

#> 
#> Attache Paket: 'ggdag'


#> Das folgende Objekt ist maskiert 'package:stats':
#> 
#>     filter

# Collider
collider <- dagify(
  P ~ S_AB,
  P ~ S_CD,
  coords = list(x = c(S_CD = 3, P = 2, S_AB =1),               y = c(S_CD = 1, P = 0,S_AB = 1)))

# Plot DAG
ggdag(collider) 









 customers <- readRDS("C:/Users/ahmed/OneDrive/Dokumente/Causal_Data_Science_Data/customer_sat.rds")

lm_customer <- lm(satisfaction ~ follow_ups , data= customers)
summary(lm_customer)

#> 
#> Call:
#> lm(formula = satisfaction ~ follow_ups, data = customers)

#> Residuals:
#>     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max

#> Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#> 
#> Residual standard error: 7.923 on 13 degrees of freedom
#> Multiple R-squared:  0.658,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.6316 
#> F-statistic: 25.01 on 1 and 13 DF,  p-value: 0.0002427



lm_customer_subscription <- lm(satisfaction ~ follow_ups + subscription , data= customers)
summary(lm_customer_subscription)

#> 
#> Call:
#> lm(formula = satisfaction ~ follow_ups + subscription, data = customers)
#> 
#> Residuals:
#>     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max

#> 
#> Coefficients:
#>                      Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
#> (Intercept)           26.7667     6.6804   4.007  0.00206 ** 
#> follow_ups             2.1944     0.7795   2.815  0.01682 *  
#> subscriptionPremium   44.7222     5.6213   7.956 6.88e-06 ***
#> subscriptionPremium+  18.0722     2.1659   8.344 4.37e-06 ***
#> ---
#> Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#> 
#> Residual standard error: 2.958 on 11 degrees of freedom
#> Multiple R-squared:  0.9597, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9487 
#> F-statistic: 87.21 on 3 and 11 DF,  p-value: 5.956e-08



cat("The realtion between satisfaction with the follow_ups for the accounts that have a subscription is more realted as the adjusted R in there is 0.9 and the Pvalue with the follow up with account to subscription is lower and the estimate has changed from -3.3093 to 2.1944  in the follow up.")

#> The realtion between satisfaction with the follow_ups for the accounts that have a subscription is more realted as the adjusted R in there is 0.9 and the Pvalue with the follow up with account to subscription is lower and the estimate has changed from -3.3093 to 2.1944  in the follow up.



library(ggplot2)

# Not conditioning on student
berk_not_cond <- ggplot(customers, aes(x = follow_ups, y = satisfaction)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = F)

# Conditioning on student  
berk_cond <- ggplot(customers, aes(x = follow_ups, y =satisfaction,color = subscription, alpha = subscription))+
   geom_point() +
   stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = F)+
  
  
   scale_alpha_manual(values = c("Subscription" = 1, "no_Subscription" = 0.2)) +theme(legend.position =      "right")

# Plot both
berk_not_cond

#> `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'








berk_cond

#> `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
